In Java, a method can either return something or return nothing.

If a method returns nothing, its return type is void.

If a method returns some value, its return type is non-void (like int, String, double, etc.).

ğŸ’¡ Rule:

When you write something inside

System.out.println( ... );

the thing inside the brackets must give some value (because println() needs something to print).

If you try to call a void method inside it, Java will give an error, because a void method doesnâ€™t return any value to print.

âŒ Example (Error Case)

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(m1()); // âŒ Error: m1() has void return type
    }

    public static void m1() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}

â¡ï¸ Here, m1() doesnâ€™t return anything â€” it only prints â€œHelloâ€.
So, when we write System.out.println(m1());, Java says:

â€œWhat should I print? m1() didnâ€™t give me any value!â€

âœ… Correct Example

If your method returns a value, then itâ€™s fine.

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(m1()); // âœ… Works fine
    }

    public static String m1() {
        return "Hello World!";
    }
}

Output:

Hello World!

